{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"8b0cbe33-32b3-4a1f-8891-2877b4565782","content":"Here's a streamlined approach for tracing .NET 8 in a Windows container on K8s:\n\n**1. Exec into the container:**\n```bash\nkubectl exec -it <pod-name> -- powershell\n```\n\n**2. Install `dotnet-trace` (if not already present):**\n```powershell\ndotnet tool install -g dotnet-trace\n```\n\n**3. Find the process ID:**\n```powershell\ndotnet-trace ps\n```\n\n**4. Collect a trace:**\n```powershell\ndotnet-trace collect -p <PID> --profile cpu-sampling --duration 00:00:30\n```\n\nThis writes a `.nettrace` file you can analyze in **Visual Studio**, **PerfView**, or **Speedscope**.\n\n**5. Copy the trace off the pod:**\n```bash\nkubectl cp <pod-name>:<path-to-trace-file> ./trace.nettrace\n```\n\n> **Tips:**\n> - If `dotnet tool` isn't available in the container image, you can [download the standalone `dotnet-trace`](https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/core/diagnostics/dotnet-trace#install) and copy it in with `kubectl cp`.\n> - For heap/GC analysis, use `dotnet-dump` with the same workflow.\n> - For continuous monitoring, consider enabling **dotnet-monitor** as a sidecar in your pod spec.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"8b85c73b-8976-44cc-a0a3-860623cead63","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking for guidance on collecting a performance trace from a .NET 8 application running in a Windows container on Kubernetes. This is a knowledge/advice question, not a code change request. I should provide concise, actionable steps.","outputTokens":406},"id":"fcdac55b-d9ab-4dc6-a78b-e333bb5fb4bd","timestamp":"2026-04-08T00:49:30.751Z","parentId":"a447bb40-0fa7-4af4-a6d7-f8dbfa54d91b"}
